title: Christianity After The End of History | Prof. Alec Ryrie on Surviving The Age of Hitler
description:
In this episode, I talk to Professor Alec Ryrie, renowned historian of Christianity and author of Protestants, to explore the harrowing intersection of Christianity and Nazi Germany. As we look back at the "Age of Hitler," we ask the difficult questions: How did the church fail, who were the few who resisted, and how does this history shape the way we live out our values today?

Professor Ryrie provides a masterclass on historical integrity, discussing the "moral revolution" of the 20th century and how the legacy of the World Wars continues to influence modern secular and religious thought.

Key Topics Covered:

The Rise of "German Christians" vs. The Confessing Church.

The moral crisis of the 1930s and 40s.

How the "Age of Hitler" redefined modern ethics.

Lessons for Christians navigating political extremism today.

title: P2: A Social History of Analytic Philosophy | Christoph Schuringa
description:
PART 2 - Christoph Schuringa is a Professor of Philosophy at Northeastern University London and editor of the *Hegel Bulletin*. His new book, "A Social History of Analytic Philosophy," challenges the notion that analytic philosophy is an apolitical pursuit of eternal truths. Instead, Schuringa argues that its enduring power and influence, particularly within elite educational institutions, are deeply rooted in specific social and political forces, demonstrating its role in upholding the status quo and liberal ideology since the post-WWII era.

title: The Anti-Woke Street Epistemology CULT: Reid Nicewonder, PF Jung & Peter Boghossian's Projection
description:
Dive deep into the world of the "anti-woke" movement as we critically examine the philosophies and rhetoric of Reid Nicewonder, PF Jung, and Peter Boghossian. This video argues that their criticisms of "wokeness" are not only deeply flawed but often reveal a pattern of projection, leading to ideologies that can be described as cult-like and harmful.

We'll explore how these figures, often positioned as "culture warriors," contribute to a divisive narrative, and why their approaches might be more about ideology than genuine intellectual discourse. From the origins of "Cultural Marxism" as a far-right scapegoat to the problematic implications of "luckpilling," we dissect the arguments that underpin their worldview.

Join us as we expose the inconsistencies and dangers within the anti-woke agenda, and understand why their philosophies are, in many ways, a projection of the very issues they claim to fight against.

title: Fascism, Christian Nationalism & Andrew Wilson
description:
Fascism isn't just a historical footnote. This video dissects the fundamental characteristics of fascist ideology, from extreme nationalism and authoritarianism to the suppression of dissent and the cult of personality. We'll explore how these elements manifested in the past and discuss why understanding them is crucial in an ever-changing world. The video also focuses on Christian Nationalism and the claims of Andrew Wilson ( @The_Crucible ) in order to evaluate whether or not Andrew meets the criteria for being a fascist.

title: Philosophy of Psychiatry: Mind & Medicine w/ Dr. Awais Aftab
description:
In this thought-provoking interview, we delve into the philosophical underpinnings of psychiatry with Dr. Awais Aftab, a psychiatrist and Clinical Assistant Professor at Case Western Reserve University specialising in the philosophy of psychiatry. We explore the historical origins of psychiatric practice, examine how concepts of "normal" and "disorder" are constructed, and investigate the complex interplay between scientific evidence and social values in psychiatric diagnosis. Dr. Aftab shares insights on the bio-psycho-social model, the challenges posed by the replication crisis, and offers a critical perspective on the future of mental health care. Whether you're interested in medicine, philosophy, or the nature of mental distress, this conversation illuminates how psychiatric practice sits at the intersection of scientific inquiry and profound philosophical questions about the human condition.

title: How Racism and the Populist Far Right Became Mainstream | Aurelien Mondon Interview
description:
Aurelien Mondon is a Senior Lecturer in Politics at the University of Bath, known for his critical research on the far right, populism, and racism. His work often examines how these political phenomena become "mainstream" through elite discourse and media narratives, challenging the idea that democracy is inherently progressive. He is the co-author of "Reactionary Democracy: How Racism and the Populist Far Right Became Mainstream" with Aaron Winter.

title: Philosophy of Luck | Aaron Rabinowitz
description:
Join me for a fascinating discussion with Aaron Rabinowitz, host of the Embracing the Void podcast, as we dive deep into his PhD thesis on the Philosophy of Luck. Aaron presents a compelling argument that at their core, all human actions are fundamentally grounded in luck. We explore how this perspective challenges traditional notions of desert and responsibility, making a powerful case for why our justice system should focus on rehabilitation rather than retribution. Don't miss this thought-provoking conversation about free will, moral responsibility, and the role of chance in shaping human behavior.

title: Rishi Sunak's DEVASTATING Question | Unveiling the Rhetorical Power of 'What is a Woman?'
description:
In a recent Prime Minister's Questions session, UK Prime Minister Rishi Sunak sparked controversy with a remark challenging his opponent's ability to define what constitutes a woman. This incident occurred on a day when the mother of Briana Ghey, a 16-year-old transgender girl who was tragically murdered, was present in Parliament. Justice Yip, in sentencing, noted that Ghey's transgender identity was a factor in the motive for her murder. Ghey's mother's presence underscored the gravity of the social and political issues entwined with her daughter's death, yet Sunak's comment seemed to exploit transgender issues for political gain.

This video aims to dissect the rhetorical significance of asking "what is a woman?" within the context of the trans-rights debate. While setting aside the moral and political implications of Sunak's statement, the focus here is on elucidating the role this question plays rhetorically and how it's not the conclusive argument some believe it to be.

The video distinguishes between two uses of asking for definitions: legitimate uncertainty and rhetorical debate framing. Legitimate uncertainty involves seeking clarity to understand differing perspectives without resorting to simplistic gotcha moments. On the other hand, rhetorical debate framing often assumes essentialism and prescriptivism, leading to stalemates rather than productive dialogue.

Viewers are advised to approach discussions by aiming for clarity rather than attempting to score points. Engaging in dialogue about how words are actually used in everyday language can lead to more fruitful exchanges. Additionally, recognizing that disagreements often stem from differing worldviews rather than incorrect definitions can facilitate progress in discussions.

By unpacking the linguistic nuances surrounding the question "what is a woman?", this video provides insights into navigating the complexities of the trans-rights debate with empathy and understanding.

0:00 Opening Monologue & Sunak 
2:29 Legimate Questions of Definitions 
5:00 Rhetorically Asking for Definitions

title: Bad Apologetics Ep 23 - Richard Swinburne "Is There A God?"
description:
In this episode James and Nathan take on the work of Oxford Christian Philosophy Richard Swinburne in his book "Is There a God?" 

James' Channel: @JamesFodor 

Swinburne's Assumptions offered without justification: 
1. A basic action is one which a person does intentionally just like that and not by doing any other intentional action.
2. Free agents require regular laws to make choices.
3. Infinity is simpler than any finite number.
4. A perfectly free person will inevitably do what he believes to be (overall) the best action and never do what he believes to be an (overall) bad action.
5. Desires are a limitation or restriction on freedom.
6. We have an obligation to do favours for those who provide a great benefit to us.
7. Creating free agents is good.
8. It is intrinsically good for God to allow us to learn and grow in the world.
9. Beauty is a good thing, even if no one observes it.
10. God has a reason to create animals who don‚Äôt have free will. 
11. It is good for God to create embodied life?
12. Every object has some essential properties and some accidental properties.
13. In discussing the laws of nature, what scientists are discussing are the powers and liabilities of innumerable particular substances.

title: Deprovincialising Science and Religion - Gregory Dawes
description:
Greg gained his first graduate degree at the Pontifical Biblical Institute in Rome (1988) before returning to New Zealand, where he completed PhD degrees in both Biblical Studies (1995) and Philosophy (2007).

He taught for some years in Theology and Religion, as well as in Philosophy. In 2010 he obtained a joint appointment, working across the two Departments.

Greg teaches Phil 229/329 (Philosophy of Religion), as well as Rels 217/317 (Religion, Science, and Magic) and Rels 225/325 (Science, Religion, and Knowledge).

His research focuses on the interaction between scientific modes of thought and those characteristic of religion. This has given rise to two books, one on the historical Jesus debate and another on the possibility of theistic explanations (explanations that appeal to a divine agent).

Greg has a new book, just published, entitled Galileo and the Conflict between Religion and Science. This offers a new defence of the 'warfare thesis', arguing that religious and scientific communities exhibit very different attitudes to knowledge, so that conflicts between the two are practically inevitable.

title: Psychology & The Supernatural - Chris French Interview
description:
Professor Chris French is the Head of the Anomalistic Psychology Research Unit in the Psychology Department at Goldsmiths, University of London. He is a Fellow of the British Psychological Society and of the Committee for Skeptical Inquiry and a Patron of the British Humanist Association. He has published over 150 articles and chapters covering a wide range of topics. His main current area of research is the psychology of paranormal beliefs and anomalous experiences. He frequently appears on radio and television casting a sceptical eye over paranormal claims. His most recent book is Anomalistic Psychology: Exploring Paranormal Belief and Experience. 

Link to Chris' website: http://profchrisfrench.com/

title: Are The Sciences Unified? - Tuomas Tahko
description:
Interview with the author of the Cambridge Elements book 'The Unity of Science' Tuomas Tahko. 
Tuomas is a Professor of Metaphysics of Science at Bristol University and Principal Investigator of the MetaScience research project (ERC grant agreement no. 771509).

title: An Orthodox perspective on LGBT Love
description:
Giacomo Sanfilippo is an Orthodox Christian, former priest, father of five and grandfather of three, and PhD candidate in Theological Studies at Trinity College in the University of Toronto. He is globally known within and beyond the Orthodox Church for his creation and management of the blog Orthodoxy in Dialogue, his MA thesis on an Orthodox theology and spirituality of same-sex love, his doctoral research on Father Pavel Florensky's theology of same-sex love, and his untiring advocacy for a better theological and pastoral response to sexual and gender diversity in human nature and ecclesial life. You can follow him on Twitter @GiacoSanfilippo.

title: Bad Apologetics Ep 13 - Reading Dr. Andrew Loke's ENTIRE book on the Resurrection!
description:
In this video Nathan, James, Kamil and Paulogia review Dr Andrew Loke's (PhD) book on the resurrection of Jesus!

0:00 Countdown 
0:23 Video Opening 
12:00 RHBS Hypothesis 
15:28 Paulogias theory 
21:18 Kamils theory
34:12 The general structure of the book and Loke's methodology
42:20 Loke and Craig's bromance
48:28 Are historians qualified for/interested in giving an alternative explanation?
51:20 Why we don't have stronger evidence (question of free will)
56:00 Why books like these are (possibly) written
59:42 Does the number of manuscripts matter?
1:08:12 Narrative flexibility as an accepted practice at the time
1:17:22 Paul as an eyewitness of the resurrection

title: Prof. Gilbert Strang Interview (@mitocw )
Bad Apologetics Ep 5 - Kalam: Refuting William Lane Craig's (@drcraigvideos )  most famous argument
description:
In this episode Nathan and James take a look at Dr. William Lane Craigs most famous argument for the existence of God - The Kalam Cosmological Argument.

0:00:00 Introduction to the episode
0:04:16 Overview of the argument
0:12:59 Why respond to this argument? 
0:25:07 Intro to the Philosophy of Time
0:34:12 A-Theory in Craigs argument
1:43:00 Philosophy of Infinity
2:27:21 Hilberts Hotel
2:57:48 Arguing from epistemic conceivability to metaphysical possibility
3:06:54 Dr Alex Malpass discusses his debate with Craig
4:23:38 Dr Malpass on the Grim Reaper Paradox
4:44:18 Dr Malpass on an actual infinite for theists
5:08:01 Dr Malpass on Gods relation to time
5:13:00 Tenseless theory of time
5:23:37 Personality and the sociology of apologetics?
5:39:20 What would make you a theist?
5:46:45 How the physics of cosmology is misrepresented
6:20:20 A deep dive into physics with James Fodor!
7:11:22 Do universes begin to exist like other things?
7:27:35 Is it likely that the cause is a disembodied mind?
8:03:34 Closing remarks

Questions for Craig:

1. Is it the first or second premise of the Kalam that is dependent on the tensed theory of time?

2. How can science support the beginning of the universe if general relativity must be interpreted non-realistically to avoid contradicting presentism?

3. What is present? How can it be that you can bring things into being by referring to them?

4. What does it mean for something to be absurd? What can we infer from something being absurd?

5. Why does the impossibility of subtraction of infinite quantities have to do with actual infinities, when any actual case involves the relative complement of an initial set?

6. What is the number of future events that will occur? How can it not be Aleph-0?

7. Why do you talk about counting down from infinity, which counting involves a starting point and the infinite universe would have no starting point?

8. How is the Grim Reaper paradox not a straightforward logical contradiction?

9. How can you appeal to the BVG and other general relativistic theorems when you believe that time is tensed, and that 4D Minkowski space should not be interpreted realistically?

10. How do you defend your misrepresentation of the scope of the papers you cite about the metastability and entropy concerns about models that avoid the BVG theorem?

11. Why can‚Äôt the universe just begin without a cause?

12. If causes are relationships between spatio-temporal events, why would the universe (which is not a spatio-temporal event) need a cause?

13. How do we know that abstract objects and personal minds are the only possible non-material entities that could have created the universe?

14. Why doesn‚Äôt an agent‚Äôs act of exercising its causal powers require a cause?

15. Why can‚Äôt a non-personal, timeless cause bring about a temporal effect?

Links to James Fodor:
Blog: https://thegodlesstheist.com/
Podcast: http://fods12.podbean.com/
Channel: https://www.youtube.com/user/TheFods12
James' Book on Amazon (Unreasonable Faith) is very reasonably priced! https://www.amazon.co.uk/Unreasonable-Faith-William-Overstates-Christianity-ebook/dp/B07DNY8PJF/ref=sr_1_1?dchild=1&keywords=unreasonable+faith&qid=1607252869&sr=8-1

title: Skepticism | Prof. Henrik Lagerlund
description:
"Henrik Lagerlund was previously Professor of Philosophy and Head of the Philosophy Department at the University of Western Ontario in Canada. He works on the history of philosophy; primarily on Medieval and Renaissance philosophy, but he has also written on Aristotle and Leibniz. He is at the moment writing a history of skepticism for Routledge. Another interest is the philosophy of food (see https://blog.apaonline.org/2017/12/07/philosophy-in-the-contemporary-world-the-philosophy-of-food/). At the Stockholm Department, he will among other things be running the Stockholm History of Philosophy Workshop - a new seminar series that will feature invited speakers in all areas of the history of philosophy." (https://www.su.se/english/profiles/hlage-1.313716)

Prof. Lagerlunds most recent book on skepticism can be found at : https://www.routledge.com/Skepticism-in-Philosophy-A-Comprehensive-Historical-Introduction/Lagerlund/p/book/9781138555563

He can also be found on twitter: @HenrikLagerlund

title: Moral Realism | Prof. Russ Shafer-Landau Interview
description:
Shafer-Landau is a graduate of Brown University and completed his PhD work at the University of Arizona under the supervision of Joel Feinberg.[1] He has been teaching philosophy at the University of Wisconsin, Madison from 2002, where he became Chair of the Department. From 1992 to 2002 Shafer-Landau taught at the University of Kansas.

He is the founder and editor of the periodical Oxford Studies in Metaethics.[2] Shafer-Landau returned to UW after a brief stint at the University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill, where he also served as the Director of the Parr Center for Ethics. Shafer-Landau is the founder and organizer for the annual Madison Metaethics Workshop (also referred to as MadMeta, founded in 2004) which followed him to North Carolina under the name "CHillMeta," before re-assuming its original identity when Shafer-Landau returned to UW. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russ_Shafer-Landau)

title: Evidence based treatments for Gender Dysphoria | Hormone Blockers What does the science say?
description:
This video: 
Joseph has a YouTube channel: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC-4OA6OQrRK2TEMKl-tQkZQ

In this video I interview Joseph on treatments for Gender Dysphoria. 

mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/gender-dysphoria/in-depth/pubertal-blockers/art-20459075 

‚ÄúPubertal blockers for transgender and gender diverse youth‚Äù
published by: Mayo Clinic 

https://mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/precocious-puberty/diagnosis-treatment/drc-20351817 ‚ÄúPrecious Puberty‚Äù published by: The Mayo Clinic

https://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/134/4/696?source=post_page-----4b76914bba52----------------------  ‚ÄúYoung Adult Psychological Outcome After Puberty Suppression and Gender Reassignment‚Äù published by: Official Journal of the American Academy of Pediatrics

This longitudal study looked at 55 young transgender adults who had received puberty suppression during adolescence 3 times. Once at age 13, another at age 16 and another at age 20 after gender reassignment surgery. The longitudinal study was done over the course of 7 years in adolescence.

‚ÄúAfter gender reassignment, in young adulthood, the Gender Dysphoria was alleviated and psychological functioning had steadily improved. Well-being was similar to or better than same-age young adults from the general population. Improvements in psychological functioning were positively correlated with postsurgical subjective well-being.‚Äù 

https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1365-2265.2009.03625.x "Hormonal therapy and sex reassignment: a systematic review and meta‚Äêanalysis of quality of life and psychosocial outcomes" pubished by: Wiley Online Library

Meta-analysis of studies concerning individuals who underwent sex reassignment surgery

80% of individuals reported significant improvement in dysphoria

78% of individuals reported significant improvement in psychological symptoms

72% of individuals reported significant improvement in sexual function

https://whatweknow.inequality.cornell.edu/topics/lgbt-equality/what-does-the-scholarly-research-say-about-the-well-being-of-transgender-people/ ‚ÄúWhat does the scholarly research say about the effect of gender transition on transgender well-being?‚Äù from Cornell University

ENORMOUS meta-analysis on transgender people and the effect gender transition has on their mental health

Of 56 studies, 52 indicated transitioning has a positive effect on the mental health of transgender people and 4 indicated it had mixed or no results.

ZERO studies indicated gender transitioning has negative results



----

Kamil will be arguing that a naturalist explanation is more probable than the traditional Christian one.

title: Euthyphro | Plato (Audiobook)
Active Listening | Carl R. Rogers, Richard E. Farson (Audiobook)
description: 2015 Reprint of 1957 Edition. Full facsimile of the original edition. Not reproduced with Optical Recognition Software. "Active Listening", first developed by Rogers and Farson, is a therapeutic technique designed to promote positive change in the client. Active listening is a communication technique used in counselling, training and conflict resolution, which requires the listener to feed back what they hear to the speaker, by way of re-stating or paraphrasing what they have heard in their own words, to confirm what they have heard and moreover, to confirm the understanding of both parties. It continues to have a lasting influence to this day.

title: Digital Gnosis | Episode #008 | Dr Daniel Hill
description:
Daniel Hill, having had his secondary education at Birkenhead School, read Literae Humaniores (Classics & Philosophy) for his BA and MA at Corpus Christi, College, Oxford, from 1991 to 1996. He then studied for an MA in Philosophy of Religion at King's College, London, from 1996 to 1997. He then studied for a PhD in Philosophy under Paul Helm and Martin Stone at the University of London from 1997 to 2001. In the year 2000 he started teaching part-time at the University of Liverpool, and was made permanent and full-time in 2011. In the meantime he also taught at the Universities of Chester, Keele, and Manchester, as well as at Merchant Taylors' School,. Crosby.

In addition to his lecturership at the University of Liverpool, he helps organize meetings of the Staff Christian Fellowship, and is always happy to be contacted by people interested in the Christian faith
